ce:section.ce:para:
Interestingly, the combination of clay and BiOBr in Clay@BiOBr exhibited higher photocatalytic performance than pure BiOBr, which may be caused by the lower recombination of photogenerated charge carriers by electron transfer from BiOBr to clay. This can be confirmed by the decreasing number of electron accumulation density in the ERDT pattern of Clay@BiOBr as shown in the numbers in rackets of Fig. 5. The photocatalytic degradation of CIP significantly increased with the decorated CQDs samples, and the highest photocatalytic performance was approximately 95% using CQDs/Clay (IS)@BiOBr-50 within 5 min of the reaction (Fig. 6a). The enhanced degradation activity of the CQDs composite maybe due to the prolonged life span of the electron–hole pairs of BiOBr in the composite. However, the excess amount of the CQDs in CQDs/Clay (IS)@BiOBr-100 decreases the CIP degradation efficiency, similar with CQDs/Clay (PM)@BiOBr-50 which used CQDs/Clay (PM) from physical mixing method show lower photocatalytic activity than CQDs/Clay (IS)@BiOBr-50. This suggests that the overloading of the CQDs on the BiOBr surface prohibit the light adsorption and act as a recombination center of electron, thereby leading to low production of photogenerated charge carrier for the degradation reaction. The photocatalytic degradation kinetics of all samples were fitted using the pseudo-first-order kinetic model (Chuaicham et al., 2021a), as shown in Fig. 6b. According to the pseudo-first-order kinetic model, the photocatalytic decomposition of CIP over the photocatalyst shows a good fit with pseudo-first-order kinetics with the regression coefficients (R

                           2
                        ) above 0.99. The reaction rate constants (k) of BiOBr, Clay@BiOBr, CQDs/Clay (IS)@BiOBr-25, CQDs/Clay (IS)@BiOBr-50, CQDs/Clay (IS)@BiOBr-100, and CQDs/Clay (PM)@BiOBr-50 are 0.137 min−1, 0.153 min−1, 0.222 min−1, 0.338 min−1, 0.265 min−1, and 0.192 min−1, respectively. The highest rate constant was obtained for CQDs/Clay (IS)@BiOBr-50, which was approximately 2.5 times higher than that of pure BiOBr and 1.7 times higher than that of CQDs/Clay (PM)@BiOBr-50. These results confirm that the optimum amount of loading of the CQDs on saponite improved the CIP degradation performance. However, the photocatalytic activities for CIP degradation decreased in the CQDs/Clay (IS)@BiOBr-100 and CQDs/Clay (PM)@BiOBr-50 composites. This indicates that the excess amount of the CQDs on the BiOBr surface blocks the light penetration to BiOBr, leading to the poor separation of photogenerated charge carriers (Chen et al., 2016b). Thus, the results proved that the combination of BiOBr with appropriate amount of clay or CQDs/Clay (IS) could significantly enhance its photocatalytic performance for the CIP degradation.
